summary.seg: This manuscript, dated by a colophon to June 1297, is an illuminated Gospel book to which a copy of the book of Revelation and some prayers were added at a later date. At some point after its original production, some standard prefatory material was added to the book, comprising the canon tables of Eusebios of Caesarea and his letter to Karpianos explaining them. The text is unusually significant for a copy of such late date, containing numerous unusual variant readings, and it has been used as a witness for many New Testament editions.

The main body of the Gospel book was copied in a beautiful calligraphic hand by a scribe named Michael Mantylides, and is his only identified work. In his lengthy colophon (ff. 293r-293v) his name is given in disguised form, each letter being substituted by another, according to a standard cryptographic sequence. This may be a gesture of modesty, in keeping with the scribe's disparagement of the quality of his work which also appears here, a conventional gesture of self-deprecation. A later hand has added the deciphered text of the name below. The colophon records that the manuscript was paid for by a certain kyr (lord) Georgios Mougdouphes, also otherwise unknown, and includes prayers for the lifelong health of his children and his mother, as well as for their salvation and that of the scribe himself. It refers to gold, silver, gems and pearls and their unimportance to the patron compared with the chanting of prayers or scriptural texts, possibly indicating that the book originally bore a treasure binding decorated with such precious materials, as Gospel manuscripts for liturgical use sometimes did.

However, the manuscript was not originally provided, or designed to be provided, with the liturgical apparatus of lection notes that helped the reader to identify the passages to be recited during the liturgy. This was inserted later, by the same hand who added the canon tables and the text of Eusebios. These additions are difficult to date, as the person responsible used archaising script resembling those of the 12th century. Such imitations of earlier writing styles was common in Byzantium in the Palaiologan period (1258-1453), particularly in religious manuscripts.

The manuscript retains a full set of miniatures of the Evangelists, on inserted leaves somewhat smaller than those of the rest of the manuscript. They are in the style of the 10th century, and may well have been reused from a manuscript of that date (Buckton, p. 195). However, there is an alternative view that they were painted at the time of the manuscript's production, deliberately imitating the style of 10th-century exemplars (Belting, pp. 215-244). The other Evangelist portrait, that of St Luke, is on the verso of a folio bearing on its recto a miniature of Christ as the Ancient of Days, surrounded by the symbols of the four Evangelists. The style of these miniatures is more consistent with the time of the manuscript's production or later. However, they appear not to have been produced for it, as they seem too large for the folio on which they appear, which has clearly been cropped down from a significantly larger leaf, leaving narrow and uneven margins on some edges and impinging on the painted border in others. These too are therefore likely to have been reused from some other manuscript.

The leaf bearing the miniature of St Mark (f. 88) was formerly pasted in with the help of a strip of parchment bearing text in the mixed minuscule bouletée style of the 10th century. It may have originated from the same manuscript as the miniature, supposing that that is indeed of the same period (Buckton, p. 195).

The text of the Book of Revelation was added in the 14th or 15th century, and may have been produced for insertion into this manuscript, as the only quire signatures it bears are a continuation of those of the main body of the volume. It is accompanied by marginal scholia excerpted from the commentary of Andrew of Caesarea. These have been added by the copyist of this text, in two stages, some excerpts being added in the same black ink used for copying the main text and others, probably later, in the red-orange ink used for the rubric. The final portion of the manuscript is a portion of a liturgical service-book containing prayers recited by the priest, which was produced in the same general period as the copy of Revelation, but may originally have formed part of another manuscript.

seg.note: The inserted folios bearing the miniatures are of smaller, variable dimensions:

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated with the numbers [i-ii] + 2 + 3-6, 8-324 + [iii-iv], in pencil, in Arabic numerals, recto, upper right. Folio number 1 appears to have been assigned to an endleaf from a previous modern rebinding, removed in the most recent rebinding. Folio number 7 has been assigned to a leaf no longer present in the volume (as per historic foliation practices at Cambridge University Library).

There is also earlier foliation in black ink, in Arabic numerals, recto, upper right, in two successive sequences for the first two component parts of the manuscript, leaving the third unfoliated. The first sequence of this foliation runs 1-291 on ff. 3-294 and 1-22 on ff. 295-316. These numbers have been crossed out in pencil.

binding.p: Late 20th or early 21st-century Cambridge University binding with red full leather covering over millboards, with plain pastedowns.

collation.signatures: A modern quire signature in Arabic numerals, in pencil, has been added to the first folio of each quire, recto, lower right. This is the beginning of a sequence running through the whole volume.

layoutDesc.layout:
ff. 4r-5v A single column of 26 lines. 155 98
Pricking does not survive. Ruled in hardpoint, system unclassified by Leroy: there are single vertical lines marking out the margins, and no visible text lines.

handNote.p: The text of Eusebios has been added by Hand A, in an upright, archaizing mixed minuscule script, in dark brown ink, with only occasional variations in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings usually appear only at the end of lines, but occasionally also elsewhere. Breathings are both angular and round, and mute iota is absent. There is frequent decorative use of the double dot, and accentuation of nomina sacra of all lengths, though this is not consistently applied. Accents are sometimes joined to letters.
There are inclusions of letters within omicron. The epsilon-iota ligature is sometimes written without closing the loop (e.g. f. 5r, lines 1-3).
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower comma and full stop.
This hand has also provided the heading in Alexandrine majuscule script, and the canon table text in mixed minuscule, in pale red ink.
The same hand also added lection notes to the main body of the manuscript, in mixed minuscule script. Mute iota sometimes appears here, in subscript.

decoDesc.decoNote: The canon tables (ff. 6r-10r) have decorative surrounds in red ink.
The start of the text of Eusebios (f. 4r) is preceded by a simple vignette in red ink.
The text of Eusebios begins with a minor initial in red ink.

physDesc.additions: A later hand has written two prayers on f. 3r.

history.origin: This part of the manuscript was apparently produced as a supplement to the main body which follows, since the same hand appears there making additions which were not part of the original plan of work. This indicates that it was produced after June 1297, in the late 13th-15th century. The archaising character of the script, resembling one of the late 12th century, makes it difficult to date this part more exactly. .

collation.p: This part consists of 34 quires, of which two consist of twelve folios and the rest are quaternia.

list.item: Quire 28+1 ff. 11-19 An additional folio bearing a miniature has been inserted after the third original folio.
Quire 118+1 ff. 84-92 An additional folio bearing a miniature has been inserted after the fourth original folio.
Quire 178+1 ff. 133-141 An additional folio bearing a miniature has been inserted after the third original folio.
Quire 2812+1 ff. 226-238 An additional folio bearing a miniature has been inserted after the fourth original folio.

signatures.p: There are orignal quire signatures in brown ink, in Greek numerals, on the first folio of each quire, recto, lower centre, and the last folio of each quire, verso, lower centre, in a sequence beginning from the start of this part. They appear on all quires (Quires 2-35: αʹ-λδʹ), but numbers were omitted for the folios at the the beginning of the current Quire 2 and end of the current Quire 35 (the beginning and end of the original manuscript), and at the beginning of Quire 25.
Modern quire signatures in Arabic numerals, in pencil, have been added to the first folio of each quire, recto, lower right. This is part of the sequence running through the whole volume.

supportDesc.condition: There is mild water damage to the edges of some folios, and some brown stains near the tail-edge, chiefly in the earlier part of the manuscript. There is very slight worm damage to the last folios of this part (ff. 280-294). There are stains on f. 294r-294v from the turn-ins of a previous binding, prior to the addition of the later portions of the manuscript. Thin parchment has given way into a cluster of small holes in f. 104. The leaves are slightly cockled.

p.layout:
ff. 11r-12v A single column of 24 lines.
145 90
Pricking survives in the lower margin. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type Leroy 22D1. Text hangs from the lines.

ff. 14-294 A single column of 21-24 lines. 132 85
Pricking sometimes survives in all three margins, but some has been lost to cropping. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type Leroy 44D1. Text hangs from the lines. The text lines are extremely faint. The text at the end of each Gospel is arranged in a decorative tapering pattern, flanked by the final rubric to the text.

handNote.p: The main text has been copied by Michael Mantylides (Hand B), in an elegant scribal mixed minuscule script, upright or slanting slightly to the right, in dark brown ink. There is moderate variation in letter size and frequent flourishing of tails into the margin.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear only at the end of lines, except in the upper line. Breathings are round and mute iota is absent. There is decorative use of the double dot, and accentuation of all nomina sacra. The double grave accent is in use. The hyphen is used to unite words (e.g. f. 195v, line 26).
There are inclusions of letters within omicron. Enlarged theta appears in a variety of forms, with the central bar straight or wavy, attached or detached, and with or without a central dot.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower and middle commas, question mark and full stop.

Chapter lists, initial and final rubric, chapter numbers and headings, and major and minor initials have been added by Hand C, who has also added lection notes on ff. 11r-12r, in mixed minuscule script, with variable slant, in bright red ink.

Breathings are round and mute iota is either subscript (e.g. f. 293r, line 9) or a range of different transitional forms, (e.g. f. 12r, line 13, f. 87r, line 6, f. 293r, line 4). There is decorative use of the double dot, and accentuation of all nomina sacra.
Punctuation used includes the lower, middle and upper points, lower comma and full stop.
The same hand has added Gospel headings in epigraphic display majuscule, in bright red ink.

handDesc.handNote: Ammonian section numbers and lection notes have been added throughout by Hand A, in Alexandrine majuscule script, in pale red ink.

decoNote.p: Portrraits of the Evangelists accompany all four Gospels. Those of Matthew, Mark and Luke are in a 10th-century style and have either been cannibalised from an older manuscript or produced in an archaising style imitating an older exemplar. There is also a miniature of Christ as the Ancient of Days, surrounded by the symbols of the four Evangelists, on the same leaf as the miniature of St Luke. These two are of more recent date, and were perhaps painted at the time of the manuscript's original production or added when it was rebound with additional material added. However, these two miniatures seem too large for the manuscript, and this leaf too is perhaps reused from another original manuscript.

list.item: f. 139r Christ with the symbols of the Evangelists ( 195 140 )

decoNote.p: The Gospel of Matthew is preceded by a pyle, and the other three Gospels by rectangular headpieces, with vegetative or lozenge ornament, in bright red ink:-
The text of each Gospel begins with a relatively small ornamented major initial in bright red ink. Minor initials in red ink frequently appear at the beginning of lines.

additions.p: As part of the original production of the manuscript, Hand C has added marginal κεφάλαιον (chapter) numbers and τίτλοι (titles). This hand has also added lection notes on ff. 11r-12r. Hand A has later added marginal Ammonian section numbers and lection notes. The lection notes include ἀρχή and τέλος marks indicting the beginning and end of lections, which appear in the margin or squeezed into the text, as space has not been left for them, indicating that these additions were not part of the original production.
Very occasional marginal notes in later hands appear (e.g. f. 117r). On f. 88r a later hand has copied text from Mt 26:2-3.
On f. 293v another hand has written out the name of Michael Mantylides, deciphering his cryptographic rendering of his name. On f. 294v another hand has twice copied a small portion of the colophon.

Some running headers have been added in the upper outer corners in Latin script, in black ink, giving modern chapter and verse references, apparently by the same hand responsible for the earlier foliation.

history.origin:
As specified by the colophon (f. 293r-293v), the manuscript was completed in June 1297. It was copied by Michael Mantylides Mantylides, Michael (PLP 16778; RGK I 283), and commissioned and paid for by
Georgios Mougdouphes Mougdouphes, Georgios (PLP 19415).

support.material: Parchment, thick and of quite poor quality, with prominent follicles. The disposition is irregular. Quire 36: HFHFFHFHHFHFFHFH; Quire 37: HFHF; Quire 38: HFFH.

collation.p: This part consists of three quires, of which one is a ternion and the others quaternia.

signatures.p: There are orignal quire signatures in black ink, in Greek numerals, on the first folio of each quire, recto, lower right. The sequence continues from the original sequence of the preceding part. They survive on all quires (λεʹ-λζʹ).
Modern quire signatures in Arabic numerals, in pencil, have been added to the first folio of each quire, recto, lower right. This is part of the sequence running through the whole volume.

supportDesc.condition: There is mild water damage to the edges of some folios, and the leaves are slightly cockled.

layoutDesc.layout:
A single column of 25-28 lines.
152-160 98-105 There is no visible pricking or ruling.

handNote.p: The main text of this part has been copied and marginal scholia added by Hand D, in a somewhat informal Hodegon-style mixed minuscule script, slanted to the right, in black ink. The same hand has added the heading, initials and further scholia from the same commentary, in the same style, in pale orange-red ink. There is modest variation in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings usually appear only at the end of lines, but occasionally elsewhere. Breathings are round and mute iota is absent. There is frequent decorative use of the double dot, and accentuation of all nomina sacra. The double grave accent is in use.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower and middle commas, question mark and full stop.

decoDesc.decoNote: The start of the text of Revelation (f. 295r) is preceded by a simple vignette in red ink.
The text of Eusebios begins with a major initial with simple ornament, in red ink.
Minor initials in red ink frequently appear at the beginning of lines.

additions.p: On f. 316v a later hand has written a series of names: Κυριακο ὁ Κυβίου, Νικολαου ιερέος and Ευφροσινι
Also on f. 316v, another hand has added a heading for the text which follows in the next part of this manuscript: + Εὐχαι τοῦ μέγαλου Βασιλῆου.

history.origin: This part of the manuscript was probably produced as a later supplement to the main body, since the earliest surviving sequence of quire signatures on this part follows on from that one. The characteristics of the script suggest that it dates to the 14th or 15th century.

support.material: Parchment (HFHF), thick and of quite poor quality, with prominent follicles.

collation.p: This part consists of a single quire, a quaternion.

signatures.p: There is what appears to be a quire signature in red ink on the first folio of the quire, recto, lower centre. If this is a signature, it presumably pertains to a different volume of which this quire was once a part.
There is a quire signature in black ink, in Greek numerals, on the first folio of the quire, recto, lower right (ληʹ). This is part of the same sequence as that in the preceding part.

supportDesc.condition: There is mild water damage to the edges of some folios, more extensive on the outermost leaves (ff. 323-324), and the leaves are slightly cockled.

layoutDesc.layout:
A single column of 19-20 lines. 135-142 85-100
Pricking does not survive. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type Leroy 11D1bn. Text is written along the lines.

handNote.p: The text of this part has been copied by Hand E, in an informal mixed minuscule script, slanting to the right, in grey-brown ink. There is significant variation in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations usually appear only at the end of lines, and only occasionally elsewhere, but superscript word endings appear frequently throughout the line. Breathings are round and mute iota is absent. There is frequent decorative use of the double dot, and accentuation of all nomina sacra. Iota and upsilon also appear with a single dot. Accents are sometimes joined to breathings, letters, abbreviations and nomina sacra strokes.
The loop epsilon and sigma telikon are present. Distinctive letter forms include a large, bulbous and sharply slanted minuscule nu. The abbreviation of καὶ takes an unusual tilted and angular form.
Punctuation used includes the lower, middle and upper points, lower and middle commas and full stop.

decoDesc.decoNote: Minor initials in red ink appear at the begining of sections of the text.

physDesc.additions: A later hand has written a series of short prayers on f. 324v.

history.origin: This part of the manuscript appears to have been bound into it at the same time as the previous one, as its quire signature is in the same hand. However, the presence of what may be an earlier quire signature suggests that it may have been taken from an existing manuscript rather than being produced as a supplement to this one. The characteristics of the script suggest that it dates to the 14th or 15th century.
